  <text>
    <body>

      <div type="description" n="monument">
        <head>Description of Monument</head>
        <p><rs type="material" key="marmor">White marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">column base</rs>.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="description" n="text">
        <head>Description of Text</head>
        <p>Cut along upper rim.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="description" n="letters">
        <head>Description of Letters</head>
        <p>Lightly cut and very irregular; av. <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">0.03</measure>.</p>
      </div>

      <div n="date" type="description">
        <head>Date</head><p><date cert="low" notAfter="0500" notBefore="0300">Third-fourth centuries A.D.</date> (<rs type="criteria">context</rs>)</p>
      </div>

      <div n="text" lang="grc" type="edition">
        <head lang="en">Edition</head>
		<ab> <lb n="1"/><w lemma="τόπος">τόπος</w> <persName key="heptamenius1" type="aphrodisian" full="yes"><name reg="Ἑπταμήνιος">Ἑπταμηνίου</name></persName> <w lemma="καί">κὲ</w> <w lemma="γαμετή">γα<unclear reason="damage">μ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ετῆς</supplied></w>.</ab>
      </div>

      <div type="apparatus">
        <head>Apparatus</head>
        <p>Reinach read at the end <foreign lang="grc">ΚΕΠΛΝ</foreign> whence Grégoire restored <foreign lang="grc">κὲ π<supplied reason="lost">α</supplied>ν<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">τὸς τοῦ γένους</supplied><gap reason="lost"/></foreign></p>
      </div>

      <div type="translation">
        <head>Translation</head>
        <ab>Place of Heptamenios and (<seg cert="low">his</seg>) wife.</ab>
      </div>

      <div type="commentary">
        <head>Commentary</head><p>See discussion at <xref type="eAla-text" n="XI.16">XI.16</xref>.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="history" n="locations"><head>Locations</head><p><rs type="found"><rs type="monuList" key="Tetrapylon">Tetrapylon</rs>: on the base of the the second standing column
from the south, in the westernmost colonnade. This face is now to the
east—that is, facing inwards; but this may be the result of
the reconstruction of the Tetrapylon in the late fourth century.</rs>. <rs type="origLocation">Findspot.</rs>. <rs type="lastLocation">Findspot.</rs>. </p></div>

      

      

      <div type="history" n="record">
        <head>History of Recording</head>
        <p>Recorded by <rs type="visitor" key="gaudin">Gaudin</rs> (68); by the NYU expedition.</p>
      </div>

